Actually, wait - I should first check if this is even the issue. Let me re-read the confirm controller logic more carefully. On line 50-54:```javascript
if (this.triggeringElement.tagName === "BUTTON" && this.triggeringElement.form) {
  // Remove the data-confirm-message to prevent re-triggering
  this.triggeringElement.removeAttribute("data-confirm-message")
  // Submit the form
  this.triggeringElement.form.requestSubmit(this.triggeringElement)
}
```

The Rails `button_to` helper creates a button that removes its confirm attribute before submission, then calls `requestSubmit()` with the button as the submitter. This newer API should designate the button as the form's submitter, which matters for proper form handling. However, the attribute removal might inadvertently trigger the confirm handler again, or there could be a compatibility issue with how `requestSubmit()` passes the button argument.

A more reliable approach would be to set a flag after confirmation to prevent re-triggering the modal, or to submit a form copy that lacks the confirm attribute entirely. Looking at the actual implementation, `requestSubmit(button)` follows the correct syntax—the method accepts a single optional submitter parameter. The real problem might be that the button needs to remain in the DOM with its name and value intact for the form submission to work properly.

Tracing through the sequence: the click handler intercepts the button press, prevents default, displays the modal, and on confirmation removes the attribute before calling `requestSubmit`. The issue could be that `requestSubmit` is re-triggering the same click handler before the attribute removal takes effect, creating a loop, or the form simply isn't submitting as expected.

